  examples: [{ in: 'operations = ["CustomStack","push","push","pop","push","push","push","increment","increment","pop","pop","pop","pop"], values = [[3],[1],[2],[],[2],[3],[4],[5,100],[2,100],[],[],[],[]]', out: '[null,null,null,2,null,null,null,null,null,103,202,201,-1]' }],
  constraints: ['1 &lt;= maxSize &lt;= 1000', '1 &lt;= x, val &lt;= 100', '0 &lt;= k &lt;= 1000', 'At most 1000 calls.'],
  editorial: ED({ intuition: 'A plain array is the stack. The only twist is increment: naively adding val to k elements is O(k), but you can defer it with a lazy increment array so each op is O(1).', approach: ['Back the stack with an array; push respects maxSize, pop returns -1 when empty.', 'Keep a parallel <code>inc</code> array where inc[i] is added when element i is popped, and propagated to inc[i-1].', 'increment(k, val) just adds val to inc[min(k, size) - 1] — the bottom k elements inherit it on the way out.'], code: 'class CustomStack:\n    def __init__(self, maxSize):\n        self.cap = maxSize\n        self.st = []\n        self.inc = []\n    def push(self, x):\n        if len(self.st) < self.cap:\n            self.st.append(x)\n            self.inc.append(0)\n    def pop(self):\n        if not self.st:\n            return -1\n        i = len(self.st) - 1\n        add = self.inc.pop()\n        if i > 0:\n            self.inc[i - 1] += add\n        return self.st.pop() + add\n    def increment(self, k, val):\n        i = min(k, len(self.st)) - 1\n        if i >= 0:\n            self.inc[i] += val', time: 'O(1)', timeWhy: 'push, pop, and increment are all constant time with the lazy increment array.', space: 'O(maxSize)', spaceWhy: 'the value and increment arrays.', pitfalls: ['A direct loop in increment is also accepted but O(k); the lazy array keeps it O(1).'] }),
