  editorial: ED({ intuition: 'Only hits within the trailing 300-second window matter. Since timestamps never decrease, older hits can be dropped from the front of a queue.', approach: ['Store hit timestamps in a queue in arrival order.', 'On getHits(t), evict timestamps from the front that are &lt;= t - 300.', 'Return the queue size — the hits remaining in (t - 300, t].'], code: 'from collections import deque\n\nclass HitCounter:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.q = deque()\n    def hit(self, timestamp):\n        self.q.append(timestamp)\n    def getHits(self, timestamp):\n        while self.q and self.q[0] <= timestamp - 300:\n            self.q.popleft()\n        return len(self.q)', time: 'O(1) amortized', timeWhy: 'each timestamp is enqueued and evicted at most once.', space: 'O(w)', spaceWhy: 'the queue holds only hits inside the 300 s window.', pitfalls: ['The window excludes timestamp - 300, so evict hits with time &lt;= t - 300.'] }),
