  editorial: ED({ intuition: 'Keep the lower half of the numbers in a max-heap and the upper half in a min-heap, balanced in size. The median is then either the top of one heap (odd count) or the average of both tops (even count) — all in O(log n) per insert.', approach: ['Push the new value into the max-heap (lower half), then move its top into the min-heap so ordering holds.', 'If the min-heap grows larger, move its top back so the max-heap has equal or one more element.', 'findMedian returns the max-heap top when the total is odd, else the average of the two tops.'], code: 'import heapq\nclass MedianFinder:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.lo = []  # max-heap (store negatives)\n        self.hi = []  # min-heap\n    def addNum(self, num):\n        heapq.heappush(self.lo, -num)\n        heapq.heappush(self.hi, -heapq.heappop(self.lo))\n        if len(self.hi) > len(self.lo):\n            heapq.heappush(self.lo, -heapq.heappop(self.hi))\n    def findMedian(self):\n        if len(self.lo) > len(self.hi):\n            return float(-self.lo[0])\n        return (-self.lo[0] + self.hi[0]) / 2.0', time: 'O(log n) per addNum', timeWhy: 'each insert does a constant number of heap pushes/pops; findMedian is O(1).', space: 'O(n)', spaceWhy: 'the two heaps together store every number.', pitfalls: ['Rebalance after every insert so the two heaps never differ in size by more than one.', 'For even counts, average as a float so 1 and 2 give 1.5, not 1.'] }),
